                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 132.—<name type="person" key="676">Private Joseph J.
                                                Reed</name>, <name type="organization" key="507">Co.
                                                B, 8th Ill. Cav.</name>; admitted <date type="admit" when="1864-04-16">April 16, 1864</date>.  Typhoid
                                        fever.  Died <date type="death" when="1864-05-06">May
                                                6</date>.  <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi>
                                        examination <date type="autopsy" when="1864-05-06">five hours after death</date>: body slightly emaciated.
                                        The lower lobe of the left lung and the lower border of the
                                        right lung were much congested and sank in water. The heart
                                        was normal. The liver was slightly enlarged; the
                                        gall-bladder full; the spleen much congested, weighing
                                        forty-one ounces; Peyer's patches were enlarged and many of
                                        them ulcerated; the mesenteric glands were much
                                                enlarged.—<hi rend="italic"><name type="person" key="675">Act. Ass't. Surg. J. D.
                                                  Linton</name>, <name type="hospital" key="173">Harewood Hospital</name>, Washington, D. C.</hi></p>                        
